{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01DBx5LMZEyDG2JKVqA13TZS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Wait - the issue is actually that when running the uber-jar, Quarkus uses `prod` profile by default. The PostgreSQL driver is present in the uber-jar, and even though `db-kind=h2`, the PostgreSQL driver might cause issues. Let me take a different approach - just remove the PostgreSQL driver from the build entirely, since we're using H2 for standalone operation:\n\nActually, looking at the error more carefully, the problem is that Quarkus detected both H2 and PostgreSQL JDBC drivers in the classpath. With Quarkus, when there's ambiguity, it may try to connect. The simplest fix is to remove the `quarkus-jdbc-postgresql` dependency from the orders-service pom since we're running standalone with H2:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2052,"cache_read_input_tokens":135669,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2052,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":282},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"09dd8e6e-4ff1-445a-9c42-b2dfa0ace457","uuid":"f6e83007-00b6-4bcb-9b75-51e6a4d4a18c"}
