{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01WbfvoLKhsZpgXwnz6VzZZt","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# =============================================\n     2→# Quarkus Orders Service Configuration\n     3→# =============================================\n     4→\n     5→# REST API base path (replaces @ApplicationPath(\"/api\"))\n     6→quarkus.rest.path=/api\n     7→quarkus.http.port=8080\n     8→\n     9→# =============================================\n    10→# Datasource Configuration (H2 in-memory by default)\n    11→# =============================================\n    12→quarkus.datasource.db-kind=h2\n    13→quarkus.datasource.jdbc.url=jdbc:h2:mem:coffeeshop;DB_CLOSE_DELAY=-1\n    14→quarkus.datasource.username=sa\n    15→quarkus.datasource.password=\n    16→\n    17→# Hibernate ORM\n    18→quarkus.hibernate-orm.database.generation=drop-and-create\n    19→quarkus.hibernate-orm.log.sql=false\n    20→\n    21→# PostgreSQL configuration (activate with -Dquarkus.profile=postgres)\n    22→%postgres.quarkus.datasource.db-kind=postgresql\n    23→%postgres.quarkus.datasource.jdbc.url=jdbc:postgresql://${DB_HOST:localhost}:${DB_PORT:5432}/${DB_NAME:coffeeshop}\n    24→%postgres.quarkus.datasource.username=${DB_USER:cafe}\n    25→%postgres.quarkus.datasource.password=${DB_PASSWORD:cafe}\n    26→%postgres.quarkus.hibernate-orm.database.generation=update\n    27→\n    28→# =============================================\n    29→# Kafka / Reactive Messaging Configuration\n    30→# =============================================\n    31→kafka.bootstrap.servers=${KAFKA_BOOTSTRAP:localhost:9092}\n    32→\n    33→# Outgoing: barista commands\n    34→mp.messaging.outgoing.barista.connector=smallrye-kafka\n    35→mp.messaging.outgoing.barista.topic=barista-commands\n    36→mp.messaging.outgoing.barista.value.serializer=org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer\n    37→\n    38→# Outgoing: kitchen commands\n    39→mp.messaging.outgoing.kitchen.connector=smallrye-kafka\n    40→mp.messaging.outgoing.kitchen.topic=kitchen-commands\n    41→mp.messaging.outgoing.kitchen.value.serializer=org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer\n    42→\n    43→# Incoming: order updates\n    44→mp.messaging.incoming.order-updates.connector=smallrye-kafka\n    45→mp.messaging.incoming.order-updates.topic=order-updates\n    46→mp.messaging.incoming.order-updates.value.deserializer=org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringDeserializer\n    47→mp.messaging.incoming.order-updates.group.id=orders-service\n    48→mp.messaging.incoming.order-updates.auto.offset.reset=latest\n    49→mp.messaging.incoming.order-updates.failure-strategy=ignore\n    50→\n    51→# Kafka health check disabled (allows standalone startup without Kafka)\n    52→quarkus.kafka.health.enabled=false\n    53→\n    54→# =============================================\n    55→# Health checks\n    56→# =============================================\n    57→quarkus.smallrye-health.root-path=/q/health\n    58→\n    59→# =============================================\n    60→# Static resources (serve from META-INF/resources)\n    61→# =============================================\n    62→quarkus.http.enable-compression=true\n    63→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"09dd8e6e-4ff1-445a-9c42-b2dfa0ace457","uuid":"057e1e08-b1f8-4a60-92b7-9cd7db782af3"}
